1. Overview

   The Web3 Auth module is a blockchain-powered authentication module for
   Kamailio that provides digest authentication using smart contracts on
   the Oasis Sapphire blockchain. This module extends the standard auth
   module functionality by replacing the traditional password-based
   authentication with blockchain-based verification.

   The module maintains full compatibility with standard SIP digest
   authentication while using blockchain smart contracts to verify user
   credentials. It supports all standard auth functions including
   WWW-Authenticate, Proxy-Authenticate, and various authentication
   challenges.

   Key features:
     * Blockchain-based authentication via smart contracts
     * Full RFC2617 digest authentication compliance
     * Support for MD5 and SHA-256 algorithms
     * Advanced nonce management and replay protection
     * Drop-in replacement for traditional auth module

2. Dependencies

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:
     * sl - stateless reply.

   External dependencies:
     * libcurl - HTTP client library for blockchain RPC calls.

3. Configuration Examples

   3.1. Basic Configuration
   3.2. Usage in Request Routing

3.1. Basic Configuration

# Load Web3 auth module
loadmodule "auth_web3.so"

# Configure Web3 parameters
modparam("auth_web3", "web3_rpc_url", "https://sapphire.oasis.io") # testnet is
the default
modparam("auth_web3", "web3_contract_address", "0xYourContractAddress")
modparam("auth_web3", "web3_debug_mode", 1)
modparam("auth_web3", "web3_timeout", 10)

# Traditional auth parameters (still supported)
modparam("auth_web3", "secret", "your_secret_key_here")
modparam("auth_web3", "nonce_expire", 300)
modparam("auth_web3", "algorithm", "SHA-256")
modparam("auth_web3", "qop", "auth")

3.2. Usage in Request Routing

# Web3 Authentication Route
route[auth_web3] {
    # Check if request has credentials
    if (!has_credentials("$fd")) {
        # No credentials - send challenge
        www_challenge("$fd", "0");
        exit;
    }

    # Authenticate using Web3 (same function name as before!)
    # But now it calls blockchain instead of checking password
    if (!pv_www_authenticate("$fd", "0")) {
        switch ($retcode) {
            case -1:
                xlog("L_INFO", "Web3 Auth: No credentials provided\n");
                www_challenge("$fd", "0");
                break;
            case -2:
                xlog("L_INFO", "Web3 Auth: Invalid credentials\n");
                www_challenge("$fd", "16"); # stale=true
                break;
            case -3:
                xlog("L_INFO", "Web3 Auth: Stale nonce\n");
                www_challenge("$fd", "16"); # stale=true
                break;
            default:
                xlog("L_ERR", "Web3 Auth: Authentication error\n");
                sl_send_reply("500", "Server Internal Error");
        }
        exit;
    }

    # Authentication successful!
    xlog("L_INFO", "Web3 Auth: User $fU authenticated via blockchain\n");

    # For REGISTER, save location
    if (is_method("REGISTER")) {
        save("location");
    }
}

